{
  "text": ". At higher plant density of 100, 000 ha -1 more competition for resources occurred and reduced the values of different yield attributes. The individual plants growth at higher plant density was affected more due to mutual shading and greater interplant competition. The internal competition within the individual plant between vegetative and reproductive parts became more as competition between plants increased with higher plant densities. The findings of Sahoo and Maha (2007) confirmed these results. Plant density per unit area significantly influenced the green fodder yield. Increase in plant density significantly increased green fodder yield being maximum at 100, 000 ha -1 . Linear increase in green fodder yield with increasing plant density was also noticed by [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "83679381"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "83679381": {
      "title": "Production potential and nitrogen use efficiency of sweet corn (Zea mays) as influenced by different planting densities and nitrogen levels",
      "abstract": "A field experiment was conducted during rainy (kharif) season of 2005 and 2006 at New Delhi, to study the effect of planting densities and nitrogen levels on sweet corn (Zea mays L.) Taller plants with reduced plant dry weight, number of kernels/cob, 1000 kernel weight, green cob weight and kernel recovery were found with increasing planting density. The number of cobs/ha and barrenness were the highest at 1 11 111 plants /ha density. The maximum cob yield was recorded at 83,333 plants/ha, which was 19.41 % higher than 63 333 plants/ha. Further increase in planting density to 1 11 111 plants/ ha declined the 21.85 % cobs yield as compared to 83 333 plants/ha. The kernel yield and net returns were also higher at 83 333 plants/ha planting density. Nitrogen uptake and nitrogen- use efficiencies also showed the similar trend. Increasing nitrogen levels produced taller plants with increased plant dry weight, number of cobs/ha, number of kernels/cob, 1000 kernel weight, green cob weight and kernel recovery, which consequently improved the yields and returns. While, barrenness declined with increasing nitrogen levels. Highest nitrogen uptake, total availability and actual residual soil nitrogen contents were recorded at 120 kgN/ha level. Increasing nitrogen levels progressively reduced agronomic and physiological nitrogen-use efficiency. Therefore, for getting higher yield and net returns, the sweet corn should be grown with planting density of 83 333 plants/ha and fertilized with 120 kg N/ha."
    }
  }
}